Inflation in Europe jumped over food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, after 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation was 3.1 percent, reported the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union.
The official forecast predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the key interest rate, saying that a reduction, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must &quot;discourage&quot; inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent is a 15-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to soaring food and energy prices.
The futures prices of wheat rose by 88 percent, and the soybean rate also reached its highest value since 1973.
Likewise, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has risen 52 percent this year, and last month a barrel of black gold cost nearly $ 100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent in 2008 to 2.5, but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at around 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
