In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding, overloading of staff do not help stop diseases, says the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, it also saves on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John&#39;s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who got to the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but soon had to return with an MRSA infection, and one important operation could not yet be performed due to the bacteria in his body.
By December 10 this year, 1,094 nosocomial infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczová, head of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been confidently registered in hospitals, the others are unknown.
Almost two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (eg throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics will develop a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in case of temporary or permanent dysfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in patients over the years, it can cause serious nosocomial infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John&#39;s Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
&quot;Infection should not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not only there,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi, &quot;where the presence of the pathogen is not studied.&quot;
Resistant to antibiotics
&quot;We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and a mask, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in vogue
The vast majority of nosocomial infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favorable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczová.
As the infection is common in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor admitted patients and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role in this.
Most cases are revealed if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical records.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, ie that microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of drug resistance, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases either.
Sampling of microbiological samples is even rarer in the basic or outpatient treatment of patients, said Karolina Böröczová.
It saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through healthcare professionals.
That is why hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in home hospital conditions.
On the contrary, the rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina Böröczová pointed out, unfortunately we can also find that in hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and a lot of patients, which further increases the chances of infections.
According to Karolina Böröczová, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there are demonstrably fewer similar infections or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA or reduce its incidence.
The program appears to be successful, with published data showing a declining trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) is one of the priorities for preventing the development of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and nosocomial infections caused by these pathogens.
