A political message is inevitable
In this way, 139 recordings of British Air Force soldiers have already reached the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have already watched their &quot;channel&quot;.
The UK Department of Defense registered as a &quot;defense headquarters&quot; in the spring of 2007 and publishes recordings of events in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the UK Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Force in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force has published videos according to its original purpose for recruitment purposes, and according to the Ministry of Defense, they are also good at acquainting the general public with the real purpose of the army&#39;s presence abroad.
&quot;Advertising in this form costs almost nothing compared to traditional television recruitment commercials,&quot; Defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, &quot;but it also necessarily carries a political message or confirms in a special way the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government.&quot;
