Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it can come true for you if you make the right choice.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or the sea, calm as a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and intoxicating cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will find this in a complete and even richer list.
But there is much more on just one island, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
Under the Spaniards, Cuba used to be the stronghold of their conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became a warehouse and transshipment point for treasures that the Spaniards looted in America and transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
Hotel Nacional was built at the very end of the 1920s.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba by drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings grew up in Havana, and cars, which belonged to the cult symbols of the 1950s, drove along wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a homestead in San Francisco de Paula, not far from Havana, and had his yacht in Cojímar.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of Bodeguita del Medio.
And what about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls in Havana&#39;s Bodeguita.
In the bar of the expensive Hotel Nacional they will mix you a cocktail according to your wishes.
And those iconic cars from the 1950s still drive around Havana, because the once-imported sacks and fiats have long since rotted in the salty and humid air.
Although Havana, especially its oldest part, is considerably dilapidated, yet nowhere in the area are there as many beautiful colonial monuments as there.
Other places are also turning into beauty, such as Trinidad.
Given that tourism brings much-needed money, its development is green.
Over the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but especially in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers one more delight, which is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by trainers.
Steaming cane from large plantations was tied to sugar factories on narrow tracks by steam and motor trains.
Their fleet has not been renewed for many decades, so there are working machines on display, whose contours are only elsewhere in museums.
Where to go?
Most visitors to Cuba will not miss the most famous places.
And so there is no need to write much about Varadero or Havana.
Perhaps just to remind you that there is a museum in the already mentioned Hemingway homestead and whoever likes this writer should not miss a visit.
Viňales Valley One of the most picturesque corners of Cuba is the Viňales Valley in the west of the island.
Lush vegetation grows from the limestone subsoil.
Mogots, limestone clumps and rocks rise steeply from the bottom of the valley and fertile soil has taken hold in their cavities, thanks to which the weathered rocks are covered with dense vegetation.
The valley is a place where perhaps the highest quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can meet its final form by visiting one of Havana&#39;s cigar factories.
It may also be interesting to some that the Chilean part of Major Zeman was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
The slave and sugar trade brought him fame and fortune.
Wealth was transformed into the beauty and grandeur of a small town.
Colonial Spanish architecture, greatly influenced by later French settlers, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road connecting the region to the rest of the country.
That isolation helped him stay away.
Nothing was built there, so nothing crashed, everyone was glad to have a roof over their head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than one afternoon, then it is worth looking at interesting places nearby, such as Playa Ancón beach or the Sugar Valley.
In the evening, visit the Casa de la Música, which comes to life after dark and the music subsides in the morning.
Baracoa
The town in the very east of Cuba is described by some as the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly such a view is influenced by the journey itself.
The two roads leading from Guantánamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and pass through nature that has hardly been affected by human activity.
Thanks to its unspoiled nature, UNESCO has inscribed the eastern island of Cuba on the World Heritage List.
They make the best chocolates there, they have the Columbus Cross in the church (actually built about a hundred years after Columbus&#39; voyage) and from the hill where the former castle and today&#39;s Hotel El Castillo stand, you can see several table mountains, the most famous being El Yunque.
Coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, the cabaret Tropicana, the shrine of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, the sanctuary, the African religions professed by the descendants of former slaves, all of which would be many pages could be described.
But, as they rightly say, better to see once.
