Congress approved the transposition of MiFID, effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations, which were concluded today with a Congressional vote on the amendments introduced by the Senate into the bill, the government held a public hearing on regulations developing the new law, with a view to both entering into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the parties unanimously emphasized the efforts of deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the efficient functioning of markets.
MiFID, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernization of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between individual supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will make it possible to provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons, and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities intermediaries. and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for conducting transactions in financial instruments is expanding by joining regulated secondary markets with multilateral trading facilities and order internalisation systems that will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law further obliges companies providing investment services to disseminate information on the market on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and ways of dealing with risk, and requires a record of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During discussions in the Congressional Trade Commission, several adjustments were made, including the exclusion of securitized receivables as a &quot;complex&quot; financial instrument given the high risk to the investor, as demonstrated by what has happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debt. (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the Directive was used to legally define the positions that bachelors in economics and business management may hold 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which sets out the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
