Gordon Brown again found a trap he could fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although it is customary for British political scandals, this is not particularly spicy.
No orders seem to have been sold, no bills in a Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked.
But barricaded Gordon Brown would do without it being discovered that a wealthy businessman had disguised £ 650,000 ($ 1.3 million) in contributions to the ruling Labor Party for four years under other people&#39;s names and that the party had not announced it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling elections and insulted the British intelligentsia by claiming that the decision was not influenced by polls, there was hope of ensuring a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly humorous Deputy Speaker of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled Northern Rock Bank has shown weakness in management and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought-out proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people has revealed unimaginable administrative slackness.
The three retired generals started a revolt in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending because they claimed that being a commander of the armed forces was part-time work.
Now here are the many gifts of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the secretary general of the Labor (and their former watchdog of internal discipline), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading for his end.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governance difficult.
People don&#39;t trust politicians and don&#39;t like them, but they usually push away their mistrust when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not be in office for long, this postponement is gone: the government is becoming leaky, ministers are starting briefings, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one respect, Mr Brown&#39;s position is particularly difficult, as he cannot take the position of a new broom compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, problems with Northern Rock and the tax office&#39;s records are linked to decisions made by Mr Brown as finance minister.
And even though he was not directly involved in Blair&#39;s trouble, such as the lengthy investigation into political party funding caused by &quot;ranks for money,&quot; voters can safely conclude that he was.
Still, Mr. Brown&#39;s troubles aren&#39;t as bad as they seem.
The touches aren&#39;t as awful as conservatives do.
As for Mr Bean, no one has died or been explicitly deceived.
And the treatment, however painful it may be, is to deliver what Mr. Brown&#39;s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm, and slightly brutal government.
The latest uproar over political donations is a good example.
Garboid, Mr. Abrahams, who compares his gifts to charity, says he did not want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not up to him.
Laws against the anonymity of major political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr Watt, who said he knew of Mr Abrahams&#39;s actions but did not know that they were illegal, would certainly be questioned thoroughly; as well as Jon Mendlesohn, a major Labor funder who learned of tricky gifts in October.
But Mr. Brown is not involved yet; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these plots, although the bulk of the payments did not take place until after his inception in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He very quickly condemned the violation of the law by his own party, but diluted his resolve by reaching for a proven tool, a commission to investigate the matter - led in addition by a retired bishop and judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of political party funding.
This would require Labor, who is in a tight spot, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a devoted party like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
Conservatives now have a decent lead in polls; he has two years to get the voters back; and the only way to win the victory is unassailable integrity and high competence.
