Does the subprime crisis affect the US credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to flutter excitedly.
Now that the US real estate market is wither, predators have focused on the local credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses could infect $ 99 billion if inferior mortgages became infected from subprime mortgages.
Signs of tension are clear.
There is a growing number of cases of inability to repay (with more than 30 days late payment) and debited accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
HSBC announced last month that it had lost $ 1.4 billion in the US consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
However, it is still early to panic.
There are still few written-off accounts and inability to repay.
According to the rating agency Moody&#39;s, the insolvency rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below average in the third quarter.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
A change in US personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large portion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore increase regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers have deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts per month.
And confidence in the securities of secured credit cards is strong, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of the research company TowerGroup predicts that their emissions in 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct ways to spread the infection between the subprime crisis and the credit card market: when real estate lending dries up, consumers tend to borrow through credit cards.
However, credit card issuers look at cash flow rather than the value of guarantors, so falling home prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They can even be beneficial for lenders.
Consumers&#39; motivation to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their property falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up the list of priorities for repayment.
Card issuers are also able to respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of guarantee items.
&quot;It doesn&#39;t happen that one fine morning we just reconsider all the loans,&quot; said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
Although the risk of a subprime-style explosion is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
