Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden crates that were based on the red-and-white-and-white design of Brillo&#39;s soap powder paper boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 presented - with Warhol&#39;s consent - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brillo boxes in Sweden, but they are not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of fifteen boxes, which at that time rightfully entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - &quot;Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo Boxes&quot; marked Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $ 100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968, about a hundred boxes were made and displayed in Sweden, which Warhol left to him.
In fact, 105 Hulten boxes were made in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
At that time, Warhol was three years after his death.
